## Claude ↔ Codex collaboration

This repo uses the local **`codex-bridge/`** kit to make Claude and Codex
pressure-test each other's work. **Read and follow `codex-bridge/PROTOCOL.md`**
for all non-trivial work: get an independent second opinion from Codex before
and/or during the work, and have the *other* model review the diff. Drive Codex
hands-off — never make the user copy-paste.

**Share everything; never start blind.** Read `tmp/codex/memory.md` at task
start (cross-task decisions/changes — the loop appends to it automatically).
Every artifact (test logs, reviews, reconciliations) is fed verbatim to the
other model; answer Codex's numbered OPEN QUESTIONS every round.

Mode keywords the user appends to a request (Claude maps → `codex_loop.sh`):

| Keyword | Mode |
|---|---|
| `@cx-build` | `--mode build` — Codex implements; `--test '<cmd>'` enables the fix loop (red test output goes back to the same Codex thread, `--fix-rounds`, default 2); add `--claude-review` for the headless-Claude cross-review + Codex fix-or-rebut round; Claude adjudicates. |
| `@cx-guard` | `--mode guard` — Claude implements; Codex reviews over threaded rounds into a CX-NN findings ledger (pass `--spec <file>` so the reviewer knows the INTENT). Claude then writes `reconciliation.md` (`CX-NN: FIXED — …` / `CX-NN: WAIVED — …` for EVERY finding) and runs `--task <id> --step verify` until `VERDICT: CLEAN`. |
| `@cx-duel`  | `--mode duel`  — mutual-critique DEBATE loop; **round 0 is independent** (no cross-feed); both critique each round and converge; a fresh-context arbiter rules on what's left (`--no-arbiter` to skip). Read-only by default; me-driven (default) or `--auto` (needs `--seed`); `--code` to edit (Codex writes in a worktree ONLY, Claude reviews) |

Append model / effort / speed after the keyword, e.g.
`@cx-build gpt5.5 xhigh fast` → `--model gpt-5.5 --effort xhigh --fast`
(normalize `gpt5.5`→`gpt-5.5`; effort ∈ low|medium|high|xhigh; `fast` = priority
service tier). No keyword → Claude picks (build for non-trivial, inline for
trivial) and says which. Persist Codex findings; fix or explicitly waive each —
then let Codex verify the reconciliation.

Duel tail words: `auto`→`--auto`, `code`→`--code`, bare integer `N`→`--rounds N`
(default 4 rounds). `@cx-duel` defaults to me-driven + read-only and works for a
plain question (no code needed). Me-driven flags persist in the task's
`duel.env` — later steps only need `--task <id>`. Write each turn to
`claude_latest.md` (consumed per step; end with `DISAGREEMENTS REMAINING: <n>`;
converge by making the single line `CONVERGED` the last line). `--auto` REQUIRES
`--seed seed.md` (a context bundle you write first) so the headless side never
starts blind. In `--code` exactly one model writes (Codex in a worktree; the
loop refuses to run Codex writable outside it); the script never auto-merges.
Effort applies to Codex as given; the Claude side has no `xhigh` → clamped to `high`.

```bash
bash codex-bridge/doctor.sh                      # free toolchain check
bash codex-bridge/codex_loop.sh --mode build  --test 'cmd' --claude-review < spec.md
bash codex-bridge/codex_loop.sh --mode guard  --base main --spec intent.md
bash codex-bridge/codex_loop.sh --mode guard  --task <id> --step verify     # after reconciliation.md
bash codex-bridge/codex_loop.sh --mode duel   --step init < question.md     # then --step codex per round, --step finalize
bash codex-bridge/codex_loop.sh --mode duel   --auto --seed seed.md < question.md
# any mode: --dry-run previews every prompt without a paid call
```

Artifacts: `tmp/codex/tasks/<id>/` (journal.md = step log, prompts/ = exact
prompts sent). NEVER let Codex read/print generated files (`.next/`, `dist/`,
`build/`, compiled CSS) — reason on source only.

**Token accounting (automatic):** every `codex_loop.sh` run prints a `TOKENS`
breakdown in its SUMMARY and writes `usage.md`/`usage.tsv` per task (with model
and in/cached/out splits from the codex `--json` stream). Codex + headless
Claude record themselves; **when you declare a task done, run
`bash codex-bridge/claude_usage.sh end <task-id>`** to record the interactive
session too, then summarize the Codex-vs-Claude split for the user. Report
anytime with `bash codex-bridge/usage_report.sh [task-id]`.
See `codex-bridge/PROTOCOL.md` → "Token accounting".
